{
  "texts": [
    "In this section, we consider two approaches for leveraging LLMs for comparative assessment; First for when one has output token-level probabilities (Prompt-Based Classifier), and second for when only the output texts are available.",
    "Prompt-Based Classifier: If one has access to the output probabilities, an efficient method to get probability estimates of the predictions is to leverage prompt-based classifiers.",
    "Let P θ (w|x) represent an LLM's conditional language model distribution of the output sequence w given the input text x.",
    "For prompt-based classifiers, the LM probabilities of specific label words (w k) are used as a proxy for the class decisions (Liusie et al., 2023).",
    "For example in summarization assessment, given a prompt P ending in '... which summary is better', one can set w i ='Summary A' and w j ='Summary B' and define the probability that response i is better than response j as:"
  ]
}